1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:02,000
Previously on "desperate housewives"...

2
00:00:02,000 --> 00:00:03,300
Grandma's here.

3
00:00:03,300 --> 00:00:04,100
In life...

4
00:00:04,100 --> 00:00:06,100
It's a post-nuptial agreement.

5
00:00:06,100 --> 00:00:07,400
I'm not signing this.

6
00:00:07,400 --> 00:00:08,500
Aah!

7
00:00:08,500 --> 00:00:09,800
Sign it!

8
00:00:09,800 --> 00:00:11,800
Stop! You're hurting me!

9
00:00:11,800 --> 00:00:13,500
Mrs. Solis, what are you doing here?

10
00:00:13,500 --> 00:00:16,200
You can't change what's already been done.

11
00:00:16,200 --> 00:00:17,100
People leave trails.

12
00:00:17,100 --> 00:00:19,100
One of those trails will lead to Deirdre.

13
00:00:19,100 --> 00:00:20,800
I'm not taking my money to the grave.

14
00:00:20,800 --> 00:00:22,800
I'm going to use it to save your ass.

15
00:00:22,800 --> 00:00:24,900
Or who people really are.

16
00:00:24,900 --> 00:00:29,300
Andrew just told me he thinks he might be gay.

17
00:00:34,200 --> 00:00:37,200
Every morning as she went to take out her trash,

18
00:00:37,200 --> 00:00:45,500
Lynette Scavo would indulge in a little daydream,
the details of which were always the same.

19
00:00:46,300 --> 00:00:53,400
One day her nasty neighbor Karen Mccluskey
would keel over and die,

20
00:00:53,700 --> 00:01:01,100
and her home would be bought by a lovely
Swedish family with two adorable twin daughters.

21
00:01:01,100 --> 00:01:05,400
The families would for man everlasting friendship,

22
00:01:05,400 --> 00:01:11,300
culminating in their daughters marrying her sons
at an elaborate wedding

23
00:01:11,300 --> 00:01:16,100
the Scavos wouldn't have to pay for.

24
00:01:17,100 --> 00:01:21,100
Yes, Lynette enjoyed her little daydream,

25
00:01:21,100 --> 00:01:27,100
but Mrs. Mccluskey always had a way
of pulling her back to reality.

26
00:01:27,100 --> 00:01:29,900
Hey, hey, hey, hey.

27
00:01:30,300 --> 00:01:32,300
Why are you stealing my garbage cans?

28
00:01:32,300 --> 00:01:35,600
Garbage pickup was two days ago, and
these cans have been on the street ever since.

29
00:01:35,600 --> 00:01:37,500
I just assumed you didn't want them anymore.

30
00:01:37,500 --> 00:01:39,800
Oh, that's very cute.
That's good.

31
00:01:39,800 --> 00:01:42,200
Here. Give them here.

32
00:01:42,200 --> 00:01:45,100
It's bad enough we got to look at that
god-awful color you painted the house.

33
00:01:45,100 --> 00:01:48,200
We shouldn't have to stare at
your cans for days on end.

34
00:01:48,200 --> 00:01:49,800
You want to talk about good neighbor etiquette?

35
00:01:49,800 --> 00:01:53,500
How about you hire a gardener
to take care of that jungle you call a lawn?

36
00:01:53,500 --> 00:01:55,200
I am on a fixed income.

37
00:01:55,200 --> 00:01:58,700
Oh. Well, perhaps you should consider
moving somewhere less expensive,

38
00:01:58,700 --> 00:02:00,000
like a nursing home.

39
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:03,000
- Go to hell.
- Run by Germans, hmm?

40
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:07,500
And you know --

41
00:02:07,500 --> 00:02:09,600
Oh. Oh.

42
00:02:09,600 --> 00:02:12,000
Mrs. -- Mrs. Mccluskey.

43
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:14,500
Mrs. Mccluskey, are you all right?

44
00:02:16,400 --> 00:02:18,200
I'll get the door.

45
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:21,900
Mrs. Mccluskey.

46
00:02:21,900 --> 00:02:27,800
For a brief moment, Lynette was presented
with an interesting choice of options.

47
00:02:29,400 --> 00:02:32,600
And though she knew she'd hate
herself in the morning,

48
00:02:32,600 --> 00:02:35,400
Lynette chose to do the right thing.

49
00:02:35,400 --> 00:02:37,400
Lynette, where are they taking me?

50
00:02:37,400 --> 00:02:41,100
You're going to the hospital, Mrs. Mccluskey.
You're going to be fine.

51
00:02:41,100 --> 00:02:42,600
I don't want to go alone.
Come with me.

52
00:02:42,600 --> 00:02:49,300
Oh, um, these are trained technicians,
and I've got a roast in the... freezer.

53
00:02:49,800 --> 00:02:52,900
Please. I'm scared.

54
00:02:55,500 --> 00:02:57,100
Yeah, I'll come with you.

55
00:02:57,100 --> 00:03:00,000
Okay, here I am. Thank you.

56
00:03:01,100 --> 00:03:04,000
If I die, I don't want it to be with strangers.

57
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:05,800
You're not going to die.

58
00:03:05,800 --> 00:03:08,500
How can you be so sure?

59
00:03:09,400 --> 00:03:12,900
Of course, Lynette didn't respond.

60
00:03:12,900 --> 00:03:20,000
How could she tell her neighbor that some dreams
were just too beautiful to come true?

61
00:03:59,800 --> 00:04:04,000
<font color=F62B97>Episode 19 : Live Alone and Like It
(a.k.a. An Unexpected Song)

62
00:04:07,400 --> 00:04:09,800
Life is a journey,

63
00:04:09,800 --> 00:04:14,900
one that is much better traveled
with a companion by our side.

64
00:04:14,900 --> 00:04:19,700
But sometimes we lose
our companions along the way,

65
00:04:20,400 --> 00:04:24,200
and then the journey becomes unbearable.

66
00:04:24,200 --> 00:04:26,100
Noah.

67
00:04:27,400 --> 00:04:29,100
Didn't know you were a religious man.

68
00:04:29,100 --> 00:04:31,600
What's with the rosary?

69
00:04:32,200 --> 00:04:34,200
They found Dierdre.

70
00:04:34,200 --> 00:04:35,600
What?

71
00:04:37,300 --> 00:04:40,700
Her body had been stuffed inside a toy chest.

72
00:04:41,500 --> 00:04:43,600
Can you believe that?

73
00:04:43,600 --> 00:04:46,000
A kid's toy chest.

74
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:53,400
She'd been dismembered.

75
00:04:59,600 --> 00:05:01,400
Oh, my god.

76
00:05:03,600 --> 00:05:07,100
Cops I.D.'D her from her dental records.

77
00:05:09,400 --> 00:05:12,600
She's been dead 15 years.

78
00:05:13,900 --> 00:05:17,100
All that time I was looking for her,

79
00:05:17,100 --> 00:05:20,100
she was already gone.

80
00:05:21,400 --> 00:05:24,100
I'm so sorry.

81
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:28,800
I have to bury my baby.

82
00:05:29,200 --> 00:05:32,100
I came out here to,

83
00:05:32,100 --> 00:05:35,500
Uh... figure out what kind of
Tombstone to get her.

84
00:05:36,400 --> 00:05:38,300
You shouldn't be doing this now.

85
00:05:38,300 --> 00:05:40,300
Let's get you home.

86
00:05:41,800 --> 00:05:44,200
There's a cop I want you to talk to.

87
00:05:44,200 --> 00:05:45,000
A cop?

88
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:47,100
His name is Sullivan.

89
00:05:47,100 --> 00:05:50,700
I paid him to take the heat off you
for your neighbor's murder.

90
00:05:50,700 --> 00:05:53,800
He'll get you the file on Dierdre's case.

91
00:05:54,300 --> 00:05:57,200
Apparently, they have some leads.

92
00:06:04,700 --> 00:06:07,500
I don't know.
I think we may be making a huge mistake.

93
00:06:07,500 --> 00:06:09,700
We made our decision.
Let's just stick to it.

94
00:06:09,700 --> 00:06:12,300
Let's say we leave him here three more weeks.

95
00:06:12,300 --> 00:06:14,700
What's the worst that could happen?

96
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:18,000
Our son just told us that he might be gay.

97
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:21,400
There are 200 other boys in this camp.

98
00:06:21,400 --> 00:06:25,000
Now, I could explain to you what might happen
if we left him here,

99
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:29,100
but I'm a lady,
and I don't use that kind of language.

100
00:06:33,800 --> 00:06:36,200
You  know, I bet we're worrying
ourselves sick over nothing.

101
00:06:36,200 --> 00:06:37,500
This is probably just a phase.

102
00:06:37,500 --> 00:06:39,000
Exactly, so we'll get him home,

103
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:42,000
we'll get him into Christian counseling
so it won't become a lifestyle.

104
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:45,900
Well, whatever's going on with him,
he's still our son, and we love him.

105
00:06:46,300 --> 00:06:47,700
Why would you say that to me?

106
00:06:47,700 --> 00:06:52,200
Because it's obvious how freaked out you are
by the whole gay thing.

107
00:06:52,200 --> 00:06:55,200
I may be freaked out,
but that doesn't change how I feel about him.

108
00:06:55,200 --> 00:06:59,000
I'm just saying be cool.

109
00:07:01,800 --> 00:07:03,800
I can be just as cool as you can.

110
00:07:03,800 --> 00:07:06,100
All  right.

111
00:07:15,800 --> 00:07:19,000
It'll be nice to have you back.

112
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:20,800
Andrew...

113
00:07:20,800 --> 00:07:25,200
I would love you even if you were a murderer.

114
00:07:35,200 --> 00:07:37,700
Mommy, the line's not moving.

115
00:07:37,700 --> 00:07:40,400
Oh, for pete's sake.

116
00:07:46,400 --> 00:07:48,000
Mom. Mom.

117
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:49,200
- What?
- Kids are waiting.

118
00:07:49,200 --> 00:07:53,800
Oh, honey, hector here teaches salsa dancing
at the community center.

119
00:07:53,800 --> 00:07:55,500
I give private lessons, too.

120
00:07:55,500 --> 00:07:57,800
Oh, I bet you do.

121
00:07:57,800 --> 00:07:58,800
- Mom.
- What?

122
00:07:58,800 --> 00:08:01,200
Could you please not flirt
with the ice cream man?

123
00:08:01,200 --> 00:08:02,200
Why not?

124
00:08:02,200 --> 00:08:05,700
Do you need a reason beyond the fact
that he's the ice cream man?

125
00:08:06,200 --> 00:08:09,200
It's called moving on with your life.

126
00:08:09,200 --> 00:08:10,800
You just broke up
with Morty two weeks ago.

127
00:08:10,800 --> 00:08:14,100
Don't you think you can at least pretend
to mourn the relationship?

128
00:08:14,100 --> 00:08:16,200
Oh, you are such a stick in the mud.

129
00:08:16,200 --> 00:08:19,200
We should be out there having fun.

130
00:08:19,200 --> 00:08:21,100
I know what we can do tonight.

131
00:08:21,100 --> 00:08:24,700
We can go to some hip club
and get some hot guys.

132
00:08:24,700 --> 00:08:27,100
- Mom --
- oh, it'll be great.

133
00:08:27,100 --> 00:08:30,900
I'll say I'm 42, and you can be 28.

134
00:08:31,500 --> 00:08:33,100
What?

135
00:08:33,100 --> 00:08:36,600
Oh, you can pull it off.

136
00:08:41,200 --> 00:08:43,800
Mrs. Mccluskey, you're back
from the hospital already?

137
00:08:43,800 --> 00:08:47,100
Turns out I O.D.'D a little bit
on my arthritis medication.

138
00:08:47,100 --> 00:08:51,600
One pill, I can open a jar.
Four pills, I'm face-down crawling for my life.

139
00:08:51,600 --> 00:08:54,400
You'll find out about that soon enough.

140
00:08:54,700 --> 00:08:57,500
Well, I'm glad to hear you're all right.

141
00:08:57,500 --> 00:08:58,600
Here.

142
00:08:58,600 --> 00:09:01,800
My way of saying thank you
for not letting me die out there on the lawn.

143
00:09:01,800 --> 00:09:04,700
- Oh, Mrs. Mccluskey, you don't --
- keep that.

144
00:09:04,700 --> 00:09:05,800
It's genuine tiffany.

145
00:09:05,800 --> 00:09:08,700
It's been in my family for years.

146
00:09:08,800 --> 00:09:10,400
I don't know what to say.

147
00:09:10,400 --> 00:09:14,200
It's -- it's stunning. Thank you.

148
00:09:26,500 --> 00:09:27,800
I'd invite you in, but --

149
00:09:27,800 --> 00:09:29,500
well, I wanted to tell you what my doctor said.

150
00:09:29,500 --> 00:09:31,800
Seems that arthritis is the least of my problems.

151
00:09:31,800 --> 00:09:34,700
See, I had this skin tag --
or what I thought was a skin tag,

152
00:09:34,700 --> 00:09:38,000
but it turns out it might be more serious.

153
00:09:42,100 --> 00:09:43,600
What do you think you're doing?

154
00:09:43,600 --> 00:09:46,800
Please -- I can't sleep in the den anymore.
I need to sleep in a bed.

155
00:09:46,800 --> 00:09:51,700
Well, then, you might want to try a motel,
because you're not coming back in here.

156
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:55,000
How many times have I got to say I'm sorry?

157
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:57,900
Obviously, a few more.

158
00:09:58,700 --> 00:10:01,100
I am not proud of what I did.

159
00:10:01,100 --> 00:10:04,200
I admit, I was way out of line.

160
00:10:04,200 --> 00:10:06,300
You want back in this bed?

161
00:10:06,600 --> 00:10:08,500
You know what to do.

162
00:10:09,800 --> 00:10:11,400
I'm not tearing up the post-nup.

163
00:10:11,400 --> 00:10:12,400
Why not?

164
00:10:12,400 --> 00:10:16,500
Because it's the one way that I can ensure
you'll be here when I get out of jail.

165
00:10:16,600 --> 00:10:19,100
Well, then have fun at the motel.

166
00:10:19,600 --> 00:10:20,500
Fine.

167
00:10:20,500 --> 00:10:23,600
Tomorrow I'm canceling your credit cards.

168
00:10:23,600 --> 00:10:24,300
What?

169
00:10:24,300 --> 00:10:26,700
And I'm taking away your ATM as well.

170
00:10:26,700 --> 00:10:28,500
What am I supposed to do for money?

171
00:10:28,500 --> 00:10:30,800
Maybe once you see
how good you've got it here,

172
00:10:30,800 --> 00:10:32,500
you'll start treating me with a little respect.

173
00:10:32,500 --> 00:10:35,500
You want my respect?
Then tear up the post-nup.

174
00:10:35,500 --> 00:10:38,300
Give me my pillow.

175
00:10:39,200 --> 00:10:40,700
One more thing --

176
00:10:40,700 --> 00:10:43,800
if you ever hurt me again,
I will kill you.

177
00:10:43,800 --> 00:10:47,200
If you ever leave me for another man,
I'll kill you.

178
00:10:50,800 --> 00:10:55,100
Boy, with all this passion,
isn't it a shame that we're not having sex?

179
00:11:08,800 --> 00:11:10,600
I feel trapped.

180
00:11:10,600 --> 00:11:12,300
You want me to open a window?

181
00:11:12,300 --> 00:11:14,100
No, I'm talking about my life.

182
00:11:14,100 --> 00:11:16,200
Oh.

183
00:11:16,200 --> 00:11:18,300
Are we done making out?

184
00:11:18,300 --> 00:11:21,100
No, no. Keep going.

185
00:11:21,700 --> 00:11:23,600
So what's up?

186
00:11:23,600 --> 00:11:27,300
I'm unhappy with Carlos and my marriage.

187
00:11:27,300 --> 00:11:30,300
I feel like I don't have options,
and it's driving me crazy.

188
00:11:30,300 --> 00:11:33,700
Every time something went south in my life,
I always had a plan "B."

189
00:11:33,700 --> 00:11:35,300
Now I feel like I have nothing.

190
00:11:35,300 --> 00:11:37,800
What about me?
Can't I be your plan "B"?

191
00:11:37,800 --> 00:11:40,900
Damn it, John,
what is our new rule?

192
00:11:40,900 --> 00:11:42,900
Stop pretending we have a future.

193
00:11:42,900 --> 00:11:44,700
Thank you.

194
00:11:44,700 --> 00:11:46,100
Can't you just walk out?

195
00:11:46,100 --> 00:11:49,600
No, 'cause if I leave, then I'll be broke,
and that's awful.

196
00:11:49,600 --> 00:11:52,600
If I stay, then he's in control,
and that's horrifying.

197
00:11:52,600 --> 00:11:57,400
And he cut up all my credit cards,
which means I'm married to him and unable to shop,

198
00:11:57,400 --> 00:12:00,500
which is probably the worst of all possible worlds.

199
00:12:00,500 --> 00:12:02,100
I'm sorry.

200
00:12:02,100 --> 00:12:04,800
I'll  figure something out.

201
00:12:05,600 --> 00:12:07,400
I'm not much fun today.

202
00:12:07,400 --> 00:12:10,200
I'm going to go.

203
00:12:11,500 --> 00:12:13,400
Wait.

204
00:12:16,200 --> 00:12:17,200
What's this?

205
00:12:17,200 --> 00:12:22,500
You deserve nice things,
and if Mr. Solis won't provide them, I will.

206
00:12:23,200 --> 00:12:25,000
With your student credit card?

207
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:26,300
I own my own business.

208
00:12:26,300 --> 00:12:27,400
You mow lawns.

209
00:12:27,400 --> 00:12:28,400
I make good money.

210
00:12:28,400 --> 00:12:32,000
You know, I have 20 houses, and I'm this close
to getting the driving range at the country club.

211
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:32,600
I can't.

212
00:12:32,600 --> 00:12:35,500
Yes, you can.

213
00:12:41,200 --> 00:12:42,800
I'll pay it off.

214
00:12:42,800 --> 00:12:44,300
If you want.

215
00:12:44,300 --> 00:12:46,300
But you don't have to.

216
00:12:46,400 --> 00:12:50,700
Mrs. Solis...
to take care of you --

217
00:12:50,700 --> 00:12:53,100
it's my dream.

218
00:12:53,500 --> 00:12:59,100
Well, far be it from me to stand
in the way of a young man's dream.

219
00:12:59,800 --> 00:13:03,800
Okay, Tom, yeah.
I will swing by the dry cleaners after I hit the market.

220
00:13:03,800 --> 00:13:07,600
Mm, I don't know.
Porter has a dentist appointment at 4:00,

221
00:13:07,600 --> 00:13:11,100
so the, um, car might have to wait until Tomorrow.

222
00:13:11,100 --> 00:13:14,400
Okay, yeah. I love you, too. Bye-bye.

223
00:13:14,400 --> 00:13:15,300
Hi there.

224
00:13:15,300 --> 00:13:17,100
I brought you some avocados.

225
00:13:17,100 --> 00:13:18,500
I have a tree in back, but I hate them,

226
00:13:18,500 --> 00:13:21,600
and your family seems like the kind
that would eat guacamole.

227
00:13:21,600 --> 00:13:25,200
Um, Mrs. Mccluskey, thank you.
That is very nice.

228
00:13:25,200 --> 00:13:26,300
So let's make up a batch.

229
00:13:26,300 --> 00:13:28,900
Oh, um, now's not a good time.

230
00:13:28,900 --> 00:13:31,400
I'm on my way out.
I have a ton of errands.

231
00:13:31,400 --> 00:13:35,200
Oh, that's great, because my car's on the Fritz,
and I could hitch a ride.

232
00:13:35,200 --> 00:13:36,800
I need to drop by the pharmacy anyway.

233
00:13:36,800 --> 00:13:40,800
No, I can't. I'm sorry,
but I-I have a lot of things to do.

234
00:13:40,800 --> 00:13:43,400
Maybe you could take me later.
I could drop by Tomorrow.

235
00:13:43,400 --> 00:13:46,100
Mrs. Mccluskey, I'm not going to
have any time Tomorrow.

236
00:13:46,100 --> 00:13:49,600
Oh. Kind of interesting that
you can't spend two minutes with me,

237
00:13:49,600 --> 00:13:54,000
but you have no trouble taking my tiffany lamp.

238
00:13:54,200 --> 00:13:57,700
Oh, for god's sakes.

239
00:13:58,200 --> 00:13:59,700
Here.

240
00:13:59,700 --> 00:14:01,100
You should take this back.

241
00:14:01,100 --> 00:14:04,200
I-I don't have a place for it.

242
00:14:04,200 --> 00:14:06,600
But that was my thank you for saving my life.

243
00:14:06,600 --> 00:14:10,700
I know, and it was a beautiful gesture.
Really.

244
00:14:10,700 --> 00:14:12,100
But I just --

245
00:14:12,100 --> 00:14:16,900
Save it, Lynette.
I get the picture.

246
00:14:28,100 --> 00:14:29,600
Oh!

247
00:14:29,600 --> 00:14:30,000
Oh, god.

248
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:33,500
Susie, this is Tim.

249
00:14:34,400 --> 00:14:35,800
Sorry we startled you.

250
00:14:35,800 --> 00:14:39,800
Oh, uh, that's okay. I --

251
00:14:39,800 --> 00:14:43,500
