497
00:29:39,500 --> 00:29:41,900
I'm really ticklish.

498
00:29:42,500 --> 00:29:43,600
Come on!

499
00:29:43,600 --> 00:29:45,000
What's wrong?

500
00:29:45,000 --> 00:29:46,700
For god's sake, Tim, she's ticklish!

501
00:29:46,700 --> 00:29:48,700
How many times do you have to be told?

502
00:29:48,700 --> 00:29:51,100
Oh, plfft. This is so much fun.

503
00:29:51,100 --> 00:29:53,400
Come on, let's find another CD.

504
00:29:53,400 --> 00:29:56,400
Mother, don't you think it's getting a little late?

505
00:29:56,400 --> 00:29:58,300
Come on.

506
00:29:58,700 --> 00:30:01,200
You haven't even finished your schnapps.

507
00:30:08,700 --> 00:30:11,400
The perfect capper to the perfect evening.

508
00:30:11,400 --> 00:30:13,000
So good night.

509
00:30:13,000 --> 00:30:16,900
It's been lovely, and, Lamont,
good luck with all your inventions.

510
00:30:16,900 --> 00:30:19,500
Well, it's only 11:30.

511
00:30:19,600 --> 00:30:21,700
I want to hit the clubs.

512
00:30:21,700 --> 00:30:24,000
Well, I know a great place just off the interstate.
Come on.

513
00:30:24,000 --> 00:30:26,100
Let's warm up the old war wagon.

514
00:30:26,100 --> 00:30:28,300
Mom, hold it!

515
00:30:28,800 --> 00:30:31,400
You are not getting into
the car alone with those two.

516
00:30:31,400 --> 00:30:32,500
You barely know them.

517
00:30:32,500 --> 00:30:35,200
I have great instincts about people.

518
00:30:35,200 --> 00:30:37,300
I always have, Susie. You know that.

519
00:30:37,300 --> 00:30:38,600
You've been married four times.

520
00:30:38,600 --> 00:30:42,300
Yes, but twice to the same guy.

521
00:30:44,000 --> 00:30:45,500
Mother.

522
00:30:45,500 --> 00:30:47,500
Susie, please, you are embarrassing me.

523
00:30:47,500 --> 00:30:49,300
Oh, I'm embarrassing you?

524
00:30:49,300 --> 00:30:51,600
Yes, and I've had it.

525
00:30:51,600 --> 00:30:55,300
All night long,
I've been trying to get you to stop being so crabby,

526
00:30:55,300 --> 00:30:57,900
and you refuse to let me help.

527
00:30:58,300 --> 00:31:01,900
And -- and your idea of helping
is letting Tim just grope you?

528
00:31:01,900 --> 00:31:05,200
Hey! You shouldn't talk to your mother like that.
She's a fine lady.

529
00:31:05,200 --> 00:31:07,000
Tim, could you just stay out of it?

530
00:31:07,000 --> 00:31:09,300
Yeah, mind your own business.

531
00:31:09,300 --> 00:31:10,400
Hey, what's your problem, pal?

532
00:31:10,400 --> 00:31:14,100
Dude, you were feeling up her mother.
It pissed me off, too.

533
00:31:14,100 --> 00:31:17,300
Come on, Susie.
Let's go back inside.

534
00:31:17,300 --> 00:31:19,400
"Let's go back inside"?
Lamont, give it up.

535
00:31:19,400 --> 00:31:22,100
You're not getting any.

536
00:31:24,100 --> 00:31:25,600
Why are you being this way?

537
00:31:25,600 --> 00:31:28,200
Just -- I'm just trying to lighten things up.

538
00:31:28,200 --> 00:31:31,300
Stop acting like tonight was about helping me.

539
00:31:31,300 --> 00:31:35,000
You wanted to go out and have fun,
and Lamont over there needed a date.

540
00:31:35,000 --> 00:31:37,600
- That's not true.
- Oh, yes, it is.

541
00:31:39,300 --> 00:31:42,000
Okay, fine, it's true.

542
00:31:42,000 --> 00:31:44,800
I wanted to get out and have fun.
Why shouldn't I?

543
00:31:44,800 --> 00:31:47,500
You know how depressed I've been
over my breakup with Morty.

544
00:31:47,500 --> 00:31:50,100
Yeah, I do,
and that's what makes me so crazy.

545
00:31:50,100 --> 00:31:51,700
You know, the difference between you and I --

546
00:31:51,700 --> 00:31:55,800
that you could be heartbroken
and you can just move on,

547
00:31:55,800 --> 00:31:59,800
and I...
am just broken.

548
00:32:04,700 --> 00:32:07,300
I know you're sad.

549
00:32:07,300 --> 00:32:09,600
No, mom, I'm not sad.

550
00:32:09,600 --> 00:32:12,100
And I'm not crabby.

551
00:32:12,400 --> 00:32:14,000
I'm devastated,

552
00:32:14,000 --> 00:32:17,300
and you keep acting
like all I need is a couple of aspirin.

553
00:32:17,300 --> 00:32:21,800
Morty was just one guy
in a series of guys for you.

554
00:32:21,800 --> 00:32:24,300
And Mike...

555
00:32:25,200 --> 00:32:28,000
he was the one.

556
00:32:28,300 --> 00:32:31,100
Why don't you get that?

557
00:32:36,800 --> 00:32:38,600
It's Lynette.

558
00:32:40,300 --> 00:32:42,000
Hello?

559
00:32:43,300 --> 00:32:46,000
Mrs. Mccluskey?

560
00:32:48,100 --> 00:32:50,300
Mrs. Mccluskey. You all right?

561
00:32:50,300 --> 00:32:52,100
How did you get in here?

562
00:32:52,100 --> 00:32:55,700
Uh, Mr. Mullinshad a spare.

563
00:32:57,100 --> 00:32:58,100
Why didn't you open the door?

564
00:32:58,100 --> 00:33:01,200
Because I was hoping that you'd go away.

565
00:33:02,500 --> 00:33:05,100
Have you been taking your arthritis medication?

566
00:33:05,100 --> 00:33:08,400
I don't need to.
Sometimes the pain goes away by itself.

567
00:33:08,400 --> 00:33:10,000
Uh-huh.

568
00:33:10,600 --> 00:33:14,200
Is that why you didn't open the door,
because of your hands?

569
00:33:15,600 --> 00:33:22,000
Mrs. Mccluskey, do you have anyone
that could help you out -- a relative, a friend?

570
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:24,500
I'm fine.

571
00:33:25,700 --> 00:33:28,200
Okay.

572
00:33:30,700 --> 00:33:32,700
Okay.

573
00:33:32,700 --> 00:33:36,400
Uh... before you go... open these, would you?

574
00:33:36,400 --> 00:33:39,200
And -- and put out the pills.

575
00:33:41,100 --> 00:33:42,200
Yeah.

576
00:33:42,600 --> 00:33:44,300
And don't get your hands all over them.

577
00:33:44,300 --> 00:33:46,000
God knows what your kids have picked up.

578
00:33:46,000 --> 00:33:48,900
Last thing I need's a case of pinkeye.

579
00:33:50,100 --> 00:33:52,800
You're a piece of work.
You know that?

580
00:33:53,000 --> 00:33:55,600
Well, this is crazy.
Why'd they give you childproof caps?

581
00:33:55,600 --> 00:33:59,500
First thing Tomorrow, I'm taking you to the pharmacy,
and we'll get you new bottles.

582
00:33:59,500 --> 00:34:02,100
Don't do me any favors.
You don't even like me.

583
00:34:02,100 --> 00:34:04,400
I don't want you doing anything
because you feel obligated.

584
00:34:04,400 --> 00:34:08,100
Let me tell you something.
Half of life is obligations.

585
00:34:08,100 --> 00:34:11,300
You don't want to go to your husband's
company Christmas party, but you do.

586
00:34:11,300 --> 00:34:15,200
You don't want to sell candy
so your kid's band can buy piccolos, but you do it.

587
00:34:15,200 --> 00:34:17,300
You attend your third cousin's wedding.

588
00:34:17,300 --> 00:34:21,800
You pick up the dry cleaning.
That's life --it's obligations.

589
00:34:21,800 --> 00:34:24,400
And you are now my obligation,

590
00:34:24,400 --> 00:34:27,000
so Tomorrow morning, I'll pick you up,
and we'll go to the pharmacy.

591
00:34:27,000 --> 00:34:30,200
Gee, I'm touched
by your outpouring of compassion.

592
00:34:30,200 --> 00:34:32,600
We don't have to be friends.

593
00:34:32,600 --> 00:34:37,200
But we're two human beings
living on the same piece of earth.

594
00:34:37,200 --> 00:34:41,300
We can at least try
and help each other out once in a while.

595
00:34:45,400 --> 00:34:47,300
And you know what?

596
00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:52,900
I am going to take this.

597
00:34:53,500 --> 00:34:54,700
Fine.

598
00:34:54,700 --> 00:34:56,500
I'll see you Tomorrow morning.

599
00:34:56,500 --> 00:34:58,800
Pick me up at 9:00.

600
00:34:58,800 --> 00:35:00,400
And don't be late.

601
00:35:06,800 --> 00:35:10,000
Andrew, come here. I want you to see this.

602
00:35:13,000 --> 00:35:15,200
Um, what are you looking at?

603
00:35:15,200 --> 00:35:18,300
I'm looking at your baby pictures.

604
00:35:18,600 --> 00:35:20,400
Look at that one.

605
00:35:22,100 --> 00:35:23,200
How old was I there?

606
00:35:23,200 --> 00:35:26,000
Just 4 weeks old.

607
00:35:34,100 --> 00:35:39,900
I never told you this, but when I gave birth to you,
there were complications.

608
00:35:40,500 --> 00:35:45,100
The umbilical cord wrapped around your neck,
and you stopped breathing.

609
00:35:45,300 --> 00:35:48,800
The room got very quiet,
and I knew you were in trouble.

610
00:35:50,600 --> 00:35:54,700
So I turned to the doctor, and I very calmly said
that he was not to worry about me,

611
00:35:54,700 --> 00:35:58,400
that his job was to save your life.

612
00:35:58,400 --> 00:36:01,600
When I say I would die for you,

613
00:36:02,000 --> 00:36:04,600
that's not an expression.

614
00:36:05,500 --> 00:36:07,800
I mean it.

615
00:36:07,800 --> 00:36:10,600
Yeah, well, uh...

616
00:36:10,800 --> 00:36:13,700
I'm going to go eat my sandwich.

617
00:36:13,700 --> 00:36:17,400
Andrew, please,
just go and talk to Reverend Sikes.

618
00:36:17,400 --> 00:36:18,300
Oh, for god's sakes --

619
00:36:18,300 --> 00:36:20,400
he can counsel you. It can help.

620
00:36:20,400 --> 00:36:24,400
Mom, I don't need any help, all right?
I'm fine.

621
00:36:25,200 --> 00:36:26,800
Why do you keep going on about this?

622
00:36:26,800 --> 00:36:30,900
Because if you don't change who you are,
then you won't go to heaven.

623
00:36:36,900 --> 00:36:39,700
You, um...

624
00:36:39,700 --> 00:36:42,600
you -- you don't think I-I'll go to heaven?

625
00:36:42,600 --> 00:36:45,300
No, I don't.

626
00:36:45,700 --> 00:36:47,500
And I need you there.

627
00:36:47,500 --> 00:36:50,600
I would be so lonely without you.

628
00:36:55,800 --> 00:37:00,700
Well...
then I guess I better go talk to Reverend Sikes.

629
00:37:00,700 --> 00:37:02,800
Oh, Andrew.

630
00:37:03,400 --> 00:37:07,500
Thank you so much.
You don't know how much that means to me.

631
00:37:12,400 --> 00:37:16,000
Oh, my -- my gosh.
Uh, are you okay?

632
00:37:16,000 --> 00:37:19,400
Oh, yeah, I just, uh, fell down the stairs.
I'm fine.

633
00:37:19,400 --> 00:37:20,400
What's up?

634
00:37:20,400 --> 00:37:24,300
Susan still loves you.

635
00:37:25,000 --> 00:37:28,300
Wow, um...
okay.

636
00:37:28,800 --> 00:37:31,300
Look, this is not a good time
for this conversation.

637
00:37:31,300 --> 00:37:33,600
She just misses you so much.

638
00:37:33,600 --> 00:37:37,800
Sophie, I just found out
that someone I was very close to is dead.

639
00:37:37,800 --> 00:37:39,600
I've really got to figure out
what I'm going to do,

640
00:37:39,600 --> 00:37:42,600
so I just don't have time
to think about Susan right now.

641
00:37:42,600 --> 00:37:45,700
She's just very, very unhappy,
and if you could just --

642
00:37:45,700 --> 00:37:48,300
I really don't.

643
00:37:48,300 --> 00:37:51,000
I'm sorry.

644
00:38:15,500 --> 00:38:18,300
PAUL YOUNG

645
00:38:24,700 --> 00:38:30,200
I swear before almighty god
I won't reveal a word that's said here today.

646
00:38:30,700 --> 00:38:33,600
Now...
what's on your mind?

647
00:38:35,900 --> 00:38:39,700
Well, here's the thing --
I lied to my parents.

648
00:38:39,700 --> 00:38:41,500
I'm not gay.

649
00:38:41,500 --> 00:38:43,000
You're not.

650
00:38:43,000 --> 00:38:45,600
Not really.

651
00:38:45,800 --> 00:38:49,200
Look, all I know is
I wanted to get the hell out of that camp,

652
00:38:49,200 --> 00:38:51,500
so I lied to my parents,

653
00:38:51,500 --> 00:38:56,000
and I told them that I was really worried
that I was having feelings for other guys,

654
00:38:56,000 --> 00:38:59,600
and...
they did exactly what I wanted them to.

655
00:38:59,600 --> 00:39:01,200
They are such tools.

656
00:39:01,200 --> 00:39:03,800
I'm sorry, just so I'm clear --

657
00:39:03,800 --> 00:39:06,600
are you a heterosexual or aren't you?

658
00:39:06,600 --> 00:39:12,500
Look... I love vanilla ice cream, okay?

659
00:39:12,700 --> 00:39:16,700
But every now and then,
I'm probably going to be in the mood for chocolate.

660
00:39:16,700 --> 00:39:18,600
You know what I'm saying?

661
00:39:20,500 --> 00:39:26,000
I do, but god would prefer
you stick to the vanilla.

662
00:39:26,300 --> 00:39:28,300
I don't believe in god.

663
00:39:28,300 --> 00:39:29,700
You don't.

664
00:39:29,700 --> 00:39:31,200
No.

665
00:39:31,200 --> 00:39:33,200
Sorry.

666
00:39:34,500 --> 00:39:36,000
You know, your mother's
going to be devastated.

667
00:39:36,000 --> 00:39:38,800
She's been praying so hard for you to change.

668
00:39:38,800 --> 00:39:41,100
Well, that's the good news.

669
00:39:41,100 --> 00:39:43,800
I am going to change -- big time.

670
00:39:43,800 --> 00:39:46,500
I-I'm not sure I follow.

671
00:39:49,500 --> 00:39:53,000
You know what my mom said to me last night?

672
00:39:53,300 --> 00:39:56,200
She said she doesn't think I'm going to heaven.

673
00:39:56,400 --> 00:39:58,900
Can you believe that?

674
00:39:59,500 --> 00:40:02,600
I'm sure she didn't mean to hurt your feelings,

675
00:40:02,600 --> 00:40:07,700
but the only way you can know paradise
is by repenting your sins.

676
00:40:10,300 --> 00:40:13,200
When she said that to me,

677
00:40:13,200 --> 00:40:16,300
suddenly it hit me how I was going to get back at her.

678
00:40:16,300 --> 00:40:19,900
From now on,
I'm going to be so good.

679
00:40:19,900 --> 00:40:22,600
I'm going to eat my vegetables,

680
00:40:22,600 --> 00:40:26,500
I-I'm going to get good grades,
I'm going to say "yes, ma'am"and "no, ma'am."

681
00:40:26,500 --> 00:40:33,500
I'm going to make her believe
that god has delivered her this little miracle.

682
00:40:33,800 --> 00:40:38,200
Until one day,
when she least expects it,

683
00:40:38,600 --> 00:40:44,100
I'm going to do something so awful
it is going to rock her world.

684
00:40:44,100 --> 00:40:48,500
I mean, it is really going to destroy her.

685
00:40:49,800 --> 00:40:52,200
And when that day comes...

686
00:40:52,800 --> 00:40:54,400
trust me.

687
00:40:54,400 --> 00:40:57,800
I'll know paradise.

688
00:41:09,300 --> 00:41:13,300
Yes, life is a journey,

689
00:41:13,300 --> 00:41:18,200
one that is much better traveled with
a companion by our side.

690
00:41:18,200 --> 00:41:22,400
Of course, that companion
can be just about anyone.

691
00:41:22,400 --> 00:41:25,000
Mrs. Mccluskey!

692
00:41:25,300 --> 00:41:27,000
We're going to be late for the doctor.

693
00:41:27,000 --> 00:41:29,800
A neighbor on the other side of the street...

694
00:41:29,800 --> 00:41:32,900
I'm coming. Jeez, hold your water.

695
00:41:35,500 --> 00:41:37,400
There you go.

696
00:41:37,400 --> 00:41:38,600
No more post-nup.

697
00:41:38,600 --> 00:41:42,400
Or the man on the other side of the bed.

698
00:41:47,400 --> 00:41:51,400
The companion can be a mother
with good intentions...

699
00:41:51,400 --> 00:41:53,400
thank you for a wonderful service, Reverend.

700
00:41:53,400 --> 00:41:55,000
Thank you so much, Bree.

701
00:41:55,000 --> 00:41:58,300
Or a child who's up to no good.

702
00:41:58,300 --> 00:42:02,300
Very inspirational.

703
00:42:05,500 --> 00:42:08,900
Still, despite our best intentions,

704
00:42:08,900 --> 00:42:13,500
some of us will lose our companions
along the way.

705
00:42:14,400 --> 00:42:17,900
And then the journey becomes unbearable.

706
00:42:22,000 --> 00:42:27,300
You see, human beings
are designed for many things,

707
00:42:28,600 --> 00:42:33,900
but loneliness isn't one of them.

708
